In an FCC structure, the lattice constant \(a\) is related to the atomic radius \(r\) by the formula \(a = 2\sqrt{2}r\). \[ a = 2\sqrt{2} \times 127.8 \, \text{pm} \approx 362.5 \, \text{pm} \] 2. **Second Nearest Neighbor Distance**: The second nearest neighbors in an FCC structure are located along the body diagonal of the cube. The distance from a corner to the body center (second nearest neighbor) is given by \(\frac{a\sqrt{3}}{2}\). \[ \text{Distance} = \frac{a\sqrt{3}}{2} = \frac{362.5 \, \text{pm} \times \sqrt{3}}{2} \approx 313.5 \, \text{pm} \] 3. **Conversion to Meters**: Convert the distance from picometers to meters. \[ 313.5 \, \text{pm} = 313.5 \times 10^{-12} \, \text{m} \approx 3.135 \times 10^{-10} \, \text{m} \] 4. **Rounding**: Round the result to two decimal places. \[ 3.135 \times 10^{-10} \, \text{m} \approx 3.14 \times 10^{-10} \, \text{m} \] Thus, the distance of the second nearest neighbors in copper is \(\boxed{3.14 \times 10^{-10}}\) meters.
